## 5. Making Redirects Fast

### Q: Why can't we just query the database directly?

Without optimization, looking up `abc123` in a billion rows means a full table scan — checking every single row. With 100M DAU doing ~5 redirects each, that's ~600K reads/sec at peak. A single database instance with full scans can't keep up.

### Q: What does database indexing do?

A B-tree index on the `short_code` column (or making it the primary key) gives O(log n) lookups instead of O(n) full scans. Like looking up a word in a dictionary by jumping to the right section, instead of reading every page from page 1.

### Q: Why add a cache on top of indexing?

Even with indexes, disk access is ~1000x slower than memory:

| Storage | Access Time | Ops/Second |
|---------|-------------|------------|
| Memory (Redis/Memcached) | 0.0001 ms | Millions |
| SSD (indexed DB) | 0.1 ms | ~100,000 |
| HDD | 10 ms | ~100 |

Most short URLs follow the Pareto principle — 20% of links get 80% of clicks. An LRU cache stores hot URLs in memory. Cache hit → instant response. Cache miss → query DB → cache the result for next time.

### Q: What about CDNs?

Deploy redirect logic to CDN edge nodes (Cloudflare Workers, Lambda@Edge). Popular short codes get resolved geographically close to the user, never hitting the origin server. Tradeoff: more cost and complexity for lower latency. Worth it at Bit.ly scale, overkill for a startup.

