## Interview-Ready One-Liners

### "How would you design a URL shortener?"
> "It's a read-heavy lookup service. I'd use an atomic Redis counter with base62 encoding for collision-free code generation, a Redis cache layer to absorb the 1000:1 read-to-write ratio, and 302 redirects to keep control over link lifecycle."

### "How do you ensure short codes are unique?"
> "Atomic counter in Redis — every increment is unique by definition. Base62 encode it for compactness. The DB has a UNIQUE constraint as the safety net."

### "How do you handle scale?"
> "Split read and write services. Reads are served from an LRU cache (Redis). Writes use counter batching — each server grabs 1000 numbers at once to minimize Redis calls. For multi-region, assign disjoint counter ranges."

### "301 or 302 for redirects?"
> "302. It keeps every click flowing through our server, prevents stale browser caches, and lets us expire or update links without users being stuck on a cached 301."

